\section{\label{sec:4}CPL and other models with linear parametrization of EoS}

In the CPL model (i.e. $\mathrm{X} \equiv \mathrm{CPL}$) \cite{ChevPol,Linder} the parameter of EoS is the linear function with respect to the scale factor of the Universe:

\begin{eqnarray}\label{{2.23}}
\overline p_{\mathrm{CPL}}={w}(a)\overline\varepsilon_{\mathrm{CPL}},\, \,
{w}(a)&=&{w}_{0}+{w}_{1}\left(1-\frac{a}{a_{0}}\right),\\
 {w}_1 \neq 0\, ,&{}&{\nonumber}
\end{eqnarray}

where $a_0$ represents the scale factor of the Universe at the present time. We consider this EoS to be valid for a definite period of time in the past
(e.g., from last scattering \cite{Linder}). We also suppose that this EoS is still valid for some period of time in the future.

From the conservation equation  we easily get

where $A$ is a constant of integration. With the help of this equation and definition {(\ref{{2.9}})}, we obtain the expression for the fluctuation of the CPL fluid pressure:

\begin{eqnarray}\label{{2.25}}
&{}&\delta p_{\mathrm{CPL}}
=\left({w}-\frac{{w}_1\overline\varepsilon_{\mathrm{CPL}}}{a_0}\frac{da}{d\overline\varepsilon_{\mathrm{CPL}}}\right)
\delta\varepsilon_{\mathrm{CPL}} \\
&=& \left[{w}_{0}+{w}_{1}\left(1-\frac{a}{a_{0}}\right)-
\frac{1}{3}\frac{{w}_1}{{w}_1-\frac{a_0}{a}\left(1+{w}_{0}+{w}_{1}\right)}\right]\delta\varepsilon_{\mathrm{CPL}}\, .{\nonumber}
\end{eqnarray}

Then, we can determine $\delta\varepsilon_{\mathrm{CPL}}$ from Eq. {(\ref{{2.17}})}:

\begin{eqnarray}\label{{2.26}}
&{}&\delta\varepsilon_{\mathrm{CPL}} =
-\frac{A\varphi}{c^2}a^{-3\left(1+{w}_{0}+{w}_{1}\right)-1}
e^{3{w}_{1}\beta} {\nonumber} \\
&\times&\frac{\left(1+{w}_{0}+{w}_1\left(1-\beta\right)\right)^2}{{w}_{0}+{w}_1\left(1-2\beta/3\right)+\left({w}_{0}+
{w}_1\left(1-\beta\right)\right)^2} \\
&-& \frac{1}{3}\delta\varepsilon_{\mathrm{rad2}}\frac{1+{w}_{0}+{w}_1\left(1-\beta\right)}{{w}_{0}+{w}_1\left(1-2\beta/3\right)+\left({w}_{0}+
{w}_1\left(1-\beta\right)\right)^2}{\nonumber} \, ,
\end{eqnarray}

where for convenience we have introduced the notation $\beta \equiv a/a_0$. Consequently, Eq.~{(\ref{{2.16}})} takes the form

\begin{eqnarray}\label{{2.27}}
&{}&\triangle\varphi+3\mathcal{K}\varphi-\frac{\kappa c^4}{2}\delta\rho_{\mathrm{ c}} =-\frac{A \kappa \varphi}{2}a^{-3\left(1+{w}_{0}+{w}_{1}\right)+2}
e^{3{w}_{1}\beta}{\nonumber} \\
&\times&\frac{\left(1+{w}_{0}+{w}_1\left(1-\beta\right)\right)^2}{{w}_{0}+{w}_1\left(1-2\beta/3\right)+\left({w}_{0}+
{w}_1\left(1-\beta\right)\right)^2}
+\frac{\kappa c^2a^3}{2}\delta\varepsilon_{\mathrm{rad2}}{\nonumber}\\
&\times&\left[
1-\frac{1}{3}\frac{1+{w}_{0}+{w}_1\left(1-\beta\right)}{{w}_{0}+{w}_1\left(1-2\beta/3\right)+\left({w}_{0}+
{w}_1\left(1-\beta\right)\right)^2}\right]\, .
\end{eqnarray}


Since the l.h.s. of this equation does not depend on time, either each of two
remaining expressions are also independent of time (within our accuracy $O(1/a)$, bearing in mind that the r.h.s. of {(\ref{{2.27}})} has been multiplied by $a^3$), or they
must cancel each other at any arbitrary moment of time. Can this be the case? The second assumption that the second and third terms on the r.h.s. of Eq.~{(\ref{{2.27}})} can
cancel each other at any arbitrary moment of time does not work because of the presence of the exponential (with respect to the scale factor $a$) function
$\exp({3{w}_{1}\beta})$ which is linearly independent from the power functions. It can be easily seen that the first assumption does not work as well in the case ${w}_1\neq 0$ (see the details in \cite{CPL}). Therefore, perfect fluids with the CPL parametrization cannot be coupled fluids.

By performing an analysis similar to the one carried above in this section, we conclude that models with the following linear parametrization of EoS:

\begin{eqnarray}\label{{2.28}}
&{}&w(z)=w_{0}-w_{1}z=w_{0}+w_{1}\left(1-\frac{a_{0}}{a}\right)\, ,\\
&{}&w(t)=w_{0}+w_{1}\left(1-\frac{t}{t_{0}}\right)\label{2.29}
\end{eqnarray}

also cannot represent the coupled fluids \cite{CPL}.



